The Niger Delta Development Commission (NDDC) has provided financial support to the nine states in the Niger Delta region to enable them fight the coronavirus outbreak. Its acting managing director, Prof. Kemebradikumo Pondei, disclosed this yesterday during a media chat in Port Harcourt, the Rivers State capital. Pondei stated that the commission opted out of procuring equipment to support the fight against the virus in the region due to the current lockdown and logistics problems. He said: “The NDDC in the beginning, attempted to procure equipment and other things to help. “But with the lockdown and logistics problem and profiteering that is taking place, the NDDC decided to support the states in the Niger Delta region with financial support which has been passed on to the nine states to increase their capacity to contain the spread of the virus.” Pondei, who is a Professor of Medical Microbiology with specialty in Virology, said although testing is key in the fight against Coronavirus, no nation has the capacity to test everybody. The NDDC boss said: “Testing is very key but testing is also a problem. No nation has the capacity to test everybody considering the type of test required. Quite a number of nations have also made the mistake of acquiring test kits that ended up being useless.” He commended the Nigeria Centre for Disease Control (NCDC) for its effort in expanding the testing centres in the country, saying the way forward for Nigeria is to increase testing centres. Pondei said: “Right now in Nigeria, the NCDC is doing a very good work expanding the testing centres and getting requisite equipment. The way forward for Nigeria is to increase testing centres.  